<node id="2012 Metric">
  <data key="d0">2012 Metric</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">The 2012 Metric represents a set of performance measurements recorded across leading North American research institutions during 2012. These metrics appear to reflect institutional rankings or assessments based on research output, academic reputation, or similar evaluative criteria.

California Institute of Technology achieved the highest recorded value at 94.8, followed by Massachusetts Institute of Technology at 92.3. Johns Hopkins University recorded 85.8, while University of Toronto measured 81.6. Carnegie Mellon University registered 78.4, McGill University recorded 75.5, and University of British Columbia achieved 77.4. University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign recorded the lowest value among the institutions at 74.2.

The 2012 Metric data collectively demonstrates a performance hierarchy among these prominent research universities, with scores ranging from 74.2 to 94.8. The concentration of higher-scoring institutions on the West Coast and in the Northeast reflects the geographic distribution of top-tier research universities in North America during this period.&lt;SEP&gt;A recorded value of 69.3 for University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill in 2012.</data>
